repo.description: The most widely used Python to C compiler
repo.name: cython

body:
This adds support for the contents of the `typing` module. Thus `typing.List[int]` gets resolved as `list` and so forth. `typing.Tuple` gets resolved as a ctuple if possible and a regular tuple if not.

Implements https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/3883 - `typing.Optional[X]` is equivalent to `X or None`, while the annotation `X` is equivalent to `X not None`.

Most significantly it introduces a mechanism for working out if an entry is unambiguously imported from some module (which i think is necessary to do this). I really want this mechanism for https://github.com/cython/cython/pull/3400, but I thought it'd be easier to do here, in a relatively small PR. This mechanism implements https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/2025

comment_data.body:
`List[Optional[Str]]` will probably just end up interpreted as `list` - there's nothing useful that Cython can do with the "element type".

`Optional[List[Str]]` should work (i.e. `list or None`).

I'm not sure I've actually tested the nesting combinations though.

commit.message:
Largely seems to work for finding typing module and using names

Added a mechanism to track where names are imported from (where
possible) and used that to identify the typing module
Another fix (cimport check must be last)
Tidying, tuples work, annotations become "not None"
Change function name, fix for Py2
Made "import as" work with cdef defined variables

Apply suggestions from code review

Co-authored-by: scoder <stefan_ml@behnel.de>
Tests that should have been part of typing_support
Simplified lookup, fixed code-style in tests

Split lookup function into entry and module version

Also rename it

title: `typing` support
